<br>
You see, the situations we use to try to support the two different sides are always highly contrived.  &quot;Given X mob when you're in Y state then etc etc&quot;  So lets try to define some situations and do some evaluations.  Before we list some situations, however, lets set some judging criteria.<br>
<br>
First, I'll consider &quot;personal defense&quot; to be the innate HP and AC that every class has.  I would say that magicians and wizards are basically equal in this regard, and I don't expect much disagreement here.  In both cases, &quot;personal defense&quot; is rather low, and so each class has additional abilities they must use to protect themselves.<br>
<br>
What is the purpose of a defensive ability?  At the most basic level, the goal is to reduce or in some way mitigate the damage done to yourself so that you will survive.  However, one would never get very far in this game all they could do was protect themselves, no matter how good at it they might be.  Therefore, some weight must be given to the degree to which a defensive ability allows for the pursuit of other goals, most notably offense.  For each defensive ability we should look at a few things:<br>
<br>
How much damage does the ability prevent(or recover)?<br>
How long can damage be prevented at this rate?<br>
How much does the ability cost?  (Cost in terms of Time, Mana, and Money)<br>
What are the chances that the ability can fail?<br>
What are the costs of failure?<br>
What are the additional drawbacks, if any, that the ability has?<br>
How well does this ability facilitate the dealing of damage or other goals?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE CODE START--><pre>  
