<br>
Since I don't want to spend my whole life here, I'll just do situation <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  I.A</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> today.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  I. Solo vs. one mob</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
In an ideal situation, you are the puller and are fully prepared for battle.  Shields are up, phaser batteries are fully charged, proton torpedoes are armed and ready.  Pet is summoned and fully buffed, wizard is buffed with skin spell and has some distance between himself and the mob.<br>
<br>
The strategy here is usually something like this:  The wizard pulls the mob and snares, at which point he can nuke as much as he wants.  If required by the available space, he can root the mob.  The wiz generally just nukes as hard as possible until the mob dies.  Ideally, the wizard will take zero damage.  A Magician will either pull the mob on to his pet.  The pet holds off the mob, taking damage and dealing damage while the magician nukes.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  How much damage does the ability prevent(or recover)?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
In an ideal one on one situation, snare and root will effectively eliminate all damage.  The ability to keep a mob from even swinging at you often means that 100% of the damage is prevented.  This does <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>not</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> apply to mobs that can cast damage spells or mobs with a ranged attack.<br>
<br>
For the mage, damage is not really prevented at all.  The damage is diverted, however, and this is valuable.  Pets do regain hitpoints faster, and the magician can also heal the pet.  In an ideal situation, 100% of the damage will be done to the pet and not the mage.  This <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>does</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> apply to spellcasters.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  How long can damage be prevented at this rate?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
A wizard can keep a mob off him with snare for (three?) minutes at a time, and can refresh until he runs out of mana, or out of room to move.  Critical factors:  Mob resistance, mob ranged attack, and physical space.<br>
<br>
A magician can divert damage for as long as his pet is alive and has aggro.  Critical factors:  Pet hitpoints, Mob damage dealing ability, pet taunting ability, pet mitigation ability(like stun).<br>
<br>
Here is where some tests would be good.  Measure how long it takes an average xp mob to kill a pet.  Compare that to the duration of snare.  For lengthy battles, measure the amount of mana spent on reapplying snare versus healing the pet or chain summoning new pets.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  How much does the ability cost?  (Cost in terms of Time, Mana, and Money)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
A wizard must expend mana for snare at least once per battle, and must refresh it over certian intervals of time.  A mobs resistance rate can cause mana expenditure to go up.  Additionally, if the wizard needs to or chooses to use root his mana expentiture will also go up.  Casting snare takes a fairly significant amount of combat time.<br>
<br>
A magician need not spend mana on his pet every battle, however, his pet must be fully prepared before hand.  Additionally, depending on the damage dealing capabilities of the mob a magician may have to heal his pet.  A magician healing his pet spends time and mana doing so.  A magician's ability to heal is own pet is also fairly limited.  In some situations it will be impossible to outheal a mobs damage output.  Additionally, a magician pet costs the magician the ability to remain invisible, and it costs the &quot;space&quot; and danger of having a second character.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  What are the chances that the ability can fail?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
For the initial snare, there is a decent chance that it will fail totally.  For subsequent snares, the chances are lowered as a wizard can spend more mana and time reapplying snare.  Once a snare lands, however, it is extremely reliable.  Roots are no more reliable than snare, and additionally have chances to fail while in progress.<br>
<br>
A mage pet is very reliable so long as it can maintain aggro and stay alive.  If the mob has high damage output, or if the pet cannot maintain aggro, then the defensive ability of the pet will fail.  Initially, the advantage is a pet.  Once the snare lands, however, a snare is a more <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>reliable</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> means of defense for the duration of the spell.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  What are the costs of failure?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
If either of the two main abilities(pet or snare) fail, both wizards and magicians have the following options:  Stand and nuke, run away, gate.  A wizard with a skin spell up is clearly superior for both toe to toe nuking and gating away.  Otherwise the two are about even, the wizard perhaps having a slight offensive advantage in faster damage nukes.<br>
<br>
The wizard, in particular, can also attempt to reapply snare, either by channeling roots/stuns or by praying that you resist your own snare.  The idea is that if the mob is worth killing, root is a safer and more reliable way to defend yourself than trusting your hitpoints and ability to channel nukes.<br>
<br>
If the mage pet has died, he has <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>no</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> innate options other than those already mentioned.  If the mage has a root earring or a bioluminescent orb he may be able to get the battle back under control by channeling one of those item effects (root or blind, respectively).  Both of those items are also usable by a wizard.<br>
<br>
If the mage pet has simply lost aggro, a magician may be able to survive long enough for the pet to regain aggro.  All the mage really needs to do here is know when and where to move away from the mob.<br>
<br>
In both cases, the caster with failed pet/snare can expect to be vulnerable and unprepared for more combat.  However, it's worth noting that a magicians ability to use phantom armor increases the speed at which is own personal defense is full strength.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  What are the additional drawbacks, if any, that the ability has?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Snare is an AoE effect, and you risk attracting unwanted attention from other mobs in addition to snaring yourself.<br>
<br>
Pets are lower level than the owner, and typically increase the range that you can expect social mobs to come to the assistance of your target.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  How well does this ability facilitate the dealing of damage or other goals?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The main drawback of snare in a solo situation is the time it takes to cast it.  Once snare is cast, the only limit to the amount of damage you can do is the amount of time it takes for the mob to reach you, at which point you must run a bit before casting again.  Other than this, you are free to nuke as hard as possible.  Repeated casts of snare reduces your long term ability to deal damage as well.  <br>
<br>
Sometimes, however, the ability to move without being hit is an advantage.  Certianly pullers and crowd controllers sometimes appreciate a snared mob.<br>
<br>
The main drawback of the pet is aggro.  A mage cannot overnuke his pet, or the pet will no long be able to protect him.  However, within the bounds of aggro limitations a magician is free to nuke as he pleases, so long as his pet stays alive.  He doesn't generally have to move much.  If his pet needs heals, a magician must dedicate a significant amount of time and mana healing.  A magician dedicated to healing his pet is incapable of nuking, and one or two heals in a battle drastically reduces a magicians damage output.  However, the upside to all of this is that the pet is dealing melee damage.  A magician can, in some cases, win a battle without ever casting a nuke.<br>
<br>
The magician cannot move while maintaining his pets defensive worth.<br>
<br>
<br>
As you can see, this topic is just barely begun(yet there are several pages worth), and already it's becoming really hard to tell who has the advantage.  Against mobs with a high melee output, mages will have a tougher time.  Against caster mobs, wizards will.  Against mobs that move quickly or have high resistances, wizards will.  When the shit hits the fan and the primary abilities fail, the wizard has a couple of tools to fall back on that the mage doesn't.  Mages defensive ability doubles as an offensive ability, while the wizard's defensive ability potentially allows for a much greater personal damage output.<br>
<br>
Basically, I really think we should stop focusing on who sucks more at defending themselves.  I think we're in way over out heads and I doubt that anyone is going to come up with a truely satisfying answer.<br>
