I do feel that in general <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is an excellent defense.  I do not think I would want to play a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wizard</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for that very reason: I would feel naked without my pet.  I am willing to plan for and deal with those times when a pet is unavailable, but when he is, he rocks.<br>
<br>
I will admit that I have much more experience using <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> defensively than either root or snare, having only experimented with druid and shaman alts.  While I have not yet mastered kiting, it obviously requires a lot of space.  Root-Dot with the shaman though is surprisingly effective, but again requires more space than having a pet.<br>
<br>
I have no problem with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wizards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> seeking some upgrade to some particular nukes, after all they are supposed to be the masters of direct damage.  It is likely unfair that at 34ish our nukes are hardly distinguishable.  At the same time, I know <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> get a big dip in pet power at the level, and feel weakish compared to their progess in other levels.  Perhaps the larger nuke is some compensation, or perhaps both <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wizards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mages</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are underpowered at that circle.  I do not know.<br>
<br>
Each class has a tendency to dismiss and undervalue their strengths and abilities, and exagerate the value of their own weaknesses and the strengths of others.  That is why your case study was worthwhile.  I think many <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> do not fully appreciate what how wonderful instant <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is.  Far easier to complain.<br>
<br>
Burn down is important, and I am glad I can do it well enough.  Last night we had several overpulls and other moron's trains, and we had enough space so that I could aggro most of the adds onto the pet.  Healing the pet does not generate aggro, so one healer plus pet kept four adds fully occupied, and his damage shield warmed them up for the melees.  Then <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /assist</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and burn down the main target.  Methodical, successful, and no enchanter.<br>
<br>
Obviously <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wizards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> should be better than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> at burn down, but I feel I do well enough.<br>
<br>
Finally, in all the talk of caster balance, it remains my opinion that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wizards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> should be balanced first, and then the other casters balanced against them, rather like melees were balanced against <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Warriors</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Because direct damage is central to casters in general and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wizards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in particular, fixing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wizard</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> direct damage as the standard seems rational and fair.  The lack of pets just makes it easier and clearer to measure and adjust their damage output.<br>
<br>
